---
import Layout from '~/layouts/Layout.astro';
import PageHeader from '~/components/PageHeader.astro';
import DividerText from '~/components/DividerText.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="Formatting Showcase"
  description="A standalone page that demonstrates supported article formatting and UI sections."
>
  <PageHeader title="Formatting Showcase" />

  <article class="prose py-7.5" data-pagefind-body>
    <p>
      This page is a visual reference for the formatting this site supports. It lives
      outside the content directory, so it can be used as a stable playground without
      becoming a real blog post.
    </p>

    <DividerText text="Typography" />

    <h1>Heading One</h1>
    <p>
      Use this for the main topic. Paragraphs should stay short enough to scan, because
      long technical posts already ask a lot from the reader.
    </p>

    <h2>Heading Two</h2>
    <p>
      Use inline code for APIs like <code>useSyncExternalStore</code>, values like
      <code>null</code>, and filenames like <code>src/pages/index.astro</code>. You can
      also use <strong>bold text</strong>, <em>italic text</em>, <s>deleted text</s>,
      <mark>highlighted text</mark>, and regular <a href="/">links</a>.
    </p>

    <h3>Heading Three</h3>
    <p>
      Keyboard hints can use <kbd>Cmd</kbd> + <kbd>K</kbd>. Small labels can use
      <small>secondary text</small>. Abbreviations can use <abbr
        title="Application Programming Interface">API</abbr
      >.
    </p>

    <h4>Heading Four</h4>
    <h5>Heading Five</h5>
    <h6>Heading Six</h6>

    <blockquote>
      <p>
        Blockquotes are useful for a short idea worth separating from the flow. Keep them
        short, otherwise they become an article inside the article.
      </p>
    </blockquote>

    <hr />

    <DividerText text="Lists" />

    <p>Use unordered lists for related ideas:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Short, scannable points</li>
      <li>One idea per bullet</li>
      <li>No fake hierarchy unless it actually helps</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Use ordered lists for steps:</p>

    <ol>
      <li>Read the current value.</li>
      <li>Subscribe to changes.</li>
      <li>Render again when the value changes.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>Nested lists are supported, but should stay shallow:</p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        External store
        <ul>
          <li>Owns the data</li>
          <li>Notifies subscribers</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>
        React component
        <ul>
          <li>Reads a snapshot</li>
          <li>Renders UI</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>

    <DividerText text="Code" />

    <p>Plain code blocks work for quick examples.</p>

    <pre><code>{`function createCounter() {
  let count = 0;

  return {
    get() {
      return count;
    },
    increment() {
      count++;
    },
  };
}`}</code></pre>

    <p>Terminal output should be visually separate from source code.</p>

    <pre><code>{`$ node counter.js
count: 1
count: 2`}</code></pre>

    <p>Use titled code blocks in Markdown posts when the filename matters:</p>

    <div class="expressive-code">
      <figure class="frame has-title">
        <figcaption><span class="title">counterStore.ts</span></figcaption>
        <pre><code>{`type Listener = () => void;

let count = 0;
const listeners = new Set<Listener>();

export function getSnapshot() {
  return count;
}`}</code></pre>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <p>Use terminal-style blocks when showing commands:</p>

    <div class="expressive-code">
      <figure class="frame has-title is-terminal">
        <figcaption><span class="title">Terminal</span></figcaption>
        <pre><code>{`bun run build
astro build
pagefind --site dist`}</code></pre>
      </figure>
    </div>

    <DividerText text="Tables" />

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Pattern</th>
          <th>Use When</th>
          <th>Skip When</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>useState</code></td>
          <td>React owns the value</td>
          <td>The source lives outside React</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>useContext</code></td>
          <td>React passes shared values down</td>
          <td>You need external subscriptions</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>useSyncExternalStore</code></td>
          <td>React reads external state</td>
          <td>It is just local UI state</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <DividerText text="Admonitions" />

    <aside class="admonition" data-admonition-type="note" aria-label="Note">
      <p class="admonition-title" aria-hidden="true">Note</p>
      <div class="admonition-content">
        <p>Use notes for context that helps, but does not interrupt the main flow.</p>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <aside class="admonition" data-admonition-type="tip" aria-label="Tip">
      <p class="admonition-title" aria-hidden="true">Tip</p>
      <div class="admonition-content">
        <p>Use tips for practical advice the reader can apply immediately.</p>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <aside class="admonition" data-admonition-type="important" aria-label="Important">
      <p class="admonition-title" aria-hidden="true">Important</p>
      <div class="admonition-content">
        <p>
          Use important callouts for details that change how the example should be read.
        </p>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <aside class="admonition" data-admonition-type="caution" aria-label="Caution">
      <p class="admonition-title" aria-hidden="true">Caution</p>
      <div class="admonition-content">
        <p>Use cautions when a small mistake can make the result confusing.</p>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <aside class="admonition" data-admonition-type="warning" aria-label="Warning">
      <p class="admonition-title" aria-hidden="true">Warning</p>
      <div class="admonition-content">
        <p>Use warnings when the wrong move can break data, security, or user trust.</p>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <DividerText text="Dialogue" />

    <aside
      class="character-dialogue align-left"
      data-character="owl"
      aria-label="Character dialogue: owl"
    >
      <img
        class="character-dialogue-image"
        src="/owl.webp"
        alt="owl"
        loading="lazy"
        width="100"
      />
      <div class="character-dialogue-content">
        <p>Wait, so the store owns the data, and React only reads snapshots?</p>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <aside
      class="character-dialogue align-right"
      data-character="duck"
      aria-label="Character dialogue: duck"
    >
      <img
        class="character-dialogue-image"
        src="/duck.webp"
        alt="duck"
        loading="lazy"
        width="100"
      />
      <div class="character-dialogue-content">
        <p>Exactly. React renders from the snapshot and subscribes for changes.</p>
      </div>
    </aside>

    <DividerText text="Cards" />

    <section class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2 not-prose">
      <article class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4">
        <p class="mb-2 text-sm text-foreground/70">Concept</p>
        <h2 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-heading2">Snapshot</h2>
        <p class="text-sm/6">
          The value React reads from an external source during render.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4">
        <p class="mb-2 text-sm text-foreground/70">Contract</p>
        <h2 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-heading2">Subscribe</h2>
        <p class="text-sm/6">
          The function that tells React when the external value may have changed.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4">
        <p class="mb-2 text-sm text-foreground/70">Status</p>
        <h2 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-green">Ready</h2>
        <p class="text-sm/6">Use color sparingly to make status easy to scan.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4">
        <p class="mb-2 text-sm text-foreground/70">Status</p>
        <h2 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-yellow">Needs Review</h2>
        <p class="text-sm/6">Keep labels short so cards do not become noisy.</p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <DividerText text="GitHub Card" />

    <div class="github-card">
      <div class="gh-title">
        <span class="gh-avatar" style="background-image: url('/favicon.ico')"></span>
        <a class="gh-text" href="https://github.com/razrinn/site">razrinn/site</a>
        <span class="gh-icon"></span>
      </div>
      <div class="gh-description">Example rendering for the GitHub card directive.</div>
      <div class="gh-chips">
        <span class="gh-stars">123</span>
        <span class="gh-forks">4</span>
        <span class="gh-license">MIT</span>
        <span class="gh-language">TypeScript</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <DividerText text="Media" />

    <figure>
      <img src="/duck.webp" alt="Duck mascot" />
      <figcaption>A normal image with a caption.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <img src="/duck.webp" alt="Pixelated duck mascot" data-pixelated />
      <figcaption>Pixelated images are useful for sprites or tiny art.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <figure>
      <div
        class="flex aspect-video items-center justify-center rounded-xl border-8 border-foreground/10 bg-accent/8 text-center text-accent"
      >
        Embedded demo or video placeholder
      </div>
      <figcaption>A caption should explain why the media exists.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <DividerText text="Disclosure" />

    <details>
      <summary>Click to reveal the extra detail</summary>
      <p>
        Use disclosure blocks for optional context. If the reader must know it, do not
        hide it.
      </p>
    </details>

    <DividerText text="Math" />

    <p>
      Inline math is supported in content posts, like <span class="katex">O(n)</span>.
    </p>

    <div class="katex-display">
      <span class="katex">total = cache hits + network requests</span>
    </div>

    <DividerText text="Layout Sections" />

    <section class="grid gap-4 not-prose">
      <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4">
        <h2 class="mb-2 text-xl font-semibold text-heading2">Full-width Section</h2>
        <p class="text-sm/6">
          Good for summaries, next steps, and standalone explanations.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
        <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4 text-sm/6">One</div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4 text-sm/6">Two</div>
        <div class="rounded-xl border-2 border-foreground/10 p-4 text-sm/6">Three</div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <DividerText text="Actions" />

    <section class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 not-prose">
      <a class="button" href="/">Primary link</a>
      <a class="button" href="/posts">Archive link</a>
      <button type="button">Button</button>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
